    "narrative": "The LawDog lineup is anchored today by **Lawrence Butler**, whose 74.56 score marks him as our strongest play despite his lower slot in the batting order. The calculation is driven by an ideal confluence of a favorable 4.61 xERA matchup against Wacha and a 10% park boost, making him a high-upside asset for power production. **Daulton Varsho** follows closely with a 68.40 efficiency score; he benefits significantly from a 13% SP skill advantage and a strong platoon split against the right-handed Bello. Similarly, **Cal Raleigh** (66.37), **Jonathan Aranda** (66.21), and **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (66.29) form a robust mid-tier core. Specifically, **Jonathan Aranda** sees his value inflated by a 12% platoon edge, while **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** remains a vital engine for our scarcity-driven goals, as his slow-delivering opponent provides a technical boost to his stolen base probability.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Geraldo Perdomo**, who narrowly made the cut at 59.46, just ahead of **Gleyber Torres**. While **Gleyber Torres** was considered, his 37.91 score fell below our mandatory 40-point efficiency floor, largely due to a brutal matchup against the elite 2.57 xERA of Ritchie. Consequently, **Gleyber Torres** and **Wenceel Perez** were sidelined to preserve game caps. We are also tracking a major disruption as **Bryson Stott** is confirmed for a rainout; he remains on the bench alongside **Will Smith**, who is not in today's official starting lineup. Managers should monitor these developments closely, as the lack of production from the bench is necessary to avoid burning limited game capacity against unfavorable pitching matchups.",
